---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const markupExample = `<article class="product-card product-card--featured">
    <a class="link" href="/products/example/">
        <img class="image" src="/example.jpg" alt="">
        <h2 class="title">Example product</h2>
        <p class="price">£24</p>
    </a>
</article>`;

const componentCssExample = `.product-card {
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--space-m);
}

.product-card > .link {
    color: inherit;
    text-decoration: none;
}

.product-card > .link > .title {
    margin-block: 0;
}

.product-card--featured {
    border-color: var(--colour-accent);
}`;

const badExample = `.featured-product-card-box {
    margin-bottom: 16px;
}

.featured-product-card-box .product-title {
    font-size: 32px;
}

.active {
    border: 2px solid purple;
}`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="LSCSS Examples"
    description="Practical Layered Semantic CSS examples."
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Examples</p>

        <h1>
            Practical examples
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            Good CSS is easier to recognise when you can compare it with the bad
            version first. These examples show how naming, layers, ownership,
            and state look in real components instead of theory slides.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Examples sections">
        <a href="#start">Start here</a>
        <a href="#before-after">Before and after</a>
        <a href="#product-card">Component example</a>
        <a href="#practice">What to practise</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="start" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Start with the core pattern
        </h2>

        <div class="hub-card-grid">
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    <a href="#product-card">Product card</a>
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Semantic naming, shallow selectors, clear modifiers, and
                    predictable ownership.
                </p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    <a href="/live-examples/">Live examples</a>
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Rendered components connecting structure, accessibility,
                    and visible output.
                </p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    <a href="/starter-template/">Starter template</a>
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Apply folder structure, layers, and naming correctly from day one.
                </p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section id="before-after" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Before and after
        </h2>

        <p>
            Most teams do not start with clean architecture. They inherit vague
            names, deep selectors, and state classes that explain nothing.
        </p>

        <p>
            Bad version:
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={badExample} />

        <p>
            Better version:
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={componentCssExample} />

        <p>
            The goal is not prettier code for screenshots. It is predictable
            ownership and easier debugging six months later.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="product-card" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Product card markup
        </h2>

        <p>
            The component name describes the block. Child classes stay short
            because the parent already provides context.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={markupExample} language="html" />
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Product card CSS
        </h2>

        <p>
            Keep selectors shallow, use modifiers deliberately, and avoid
            turning temporary state into permanent naming decisions.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={componentCssExample} />
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Compare good and bad patterns
        </h2>

        <div class="hub-card-grid">
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    <a href="/anti-pattern-gallery/">Anti-pattern gallery</a>
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Selector chaos, specificity fights, over-nesting, and names
                    that aged badly.
                </p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    <a href="/comparisons/">Comparisons</a>
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Compare LSCSS with BEM, scoped CSS, utility-first systems,
                    and modern CSS features.
                </p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    <a href="/migration/">Migration examples</a>
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Move from legacy CSS toward a layered, semantic structure
                    without setting fire to delivery.
                </p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section id="practice" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            What to practise next
        </h2>

        <ol>
            <li>Pick a real component from an existing project.</li>
            <li>Name the parent semantically.</li>
            <li>Replace deep selectors with shallow child selectors.</li>
            <li>Add modifiers only for real reusable variants.</li>
            <li>Use explicit state classes for temporary behaviour.</li>
            <li>Place the CSS in the correct layer and partial.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
